Moapa Valley is an [unincorporated town](/Unincorporated_towns_in_Nevada) nestled in [Clark County](/Clark_County,_Nevada), [Nevada](/Nevada). \[2] This means it exists without its own municipal government, relying on the county for services, a detail that feels fitting for a place defined by what it lacks. According to the [2010 census](/2010_United_States_Census), it was home to 6,924 souls, a number which had dwindled to 6,289 by 2020, suggesting that even in the desert, people find ways to disappear. \[3] The community is situated within a valley of the same name, a long, narrow depression in the earth stretching about 40 miles (64 km), running roughly from northwest to southeast as if trying to escape its own geography.

### Geography

The lifeblood of this arid landscape is the [Muddy River](/Muddy_River_(Nevada)), which, in a rare moment of poetic accuracy, was formerly known as the Moapa River. It emerges from the geological curiosity of the [Warm Springs Natural Area](/Warm_Springs_Natural_Area) and carves its path through the valley until it surrenders its waters to [Lake Mead](/Lake_Mead). Strung along this river like beads on a fraying string are the communities of [Moapa Town](/Moapa,_Nevada), [Logandale](/Logandale,_Nevada), and [Overton](/Overton,_Nevada). Logandale sits about 12 miles (19 km) southeast of Moapa Town, and Overton is another 5 miles (8.0 km) further, a short enough distance to borrow sugar and a long enough one to maintain plausible deniability.

Before the Hoover Dam created [Lake Mead](/Lake_Mead) and humanity decided to drown the desert, the valley also held the town of [St. Thomas](/St._Thomas,_Nevada). It was methodically abandoned in 1938 as the lake waters rose, a slow-motion Atlantis for the Great Depression era.

![From Moapa Valley, looking east towards the Mormon Mesa](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Moapa_Valley_from_Overton%2C_NV.jpg/1024px-Moapa_Valley_from_Overton%2C_NV.jpg)
*From Moapa Valley, looking east towards the Mormon Mesa. A view that has remained largely unimpressed by human endeavor.*

Moapa Valley rests at an elevation of 1,265 feet (386 m), high enough to be away from the worst of the Vegas heat but not high enough to escape it entirely. The [United States Census Bureau](/United_States_Census_Bureau), in its infinite wisdom, defines the [census-designated place](/Census-designated_place) (CDP) of Moapa Valley—a boundary which may or may not align with what locals consider their town—as having a total area of 43.7 square miles (113.2 km²). Of this, an overwhelming 43.7 square miles (113.1 km²) is land. A scant 0.04 square miles (0.1 km²), or 0.05%, is water. Try not to get your feet wet. \[4]

